u>. Instead, she announced last week that she=E2=80=99d reached =E2=80=9Cth=
e top of the wave=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94true in multiple ways, it turns out=E2=
=80=94and had decided that it was time to give her children =E2=80=9Ca bigg=
er piece of my time pie.=E2=80=9D Inevitably, many television news talents =
will make similar announcements in the year ahead. As one veteran media exe=
cutive put it: =E2=80=9CSame drill, different cover story.=E2=80=9D<br/><br=
/>The great resetting of TV news
contracts is now firmly underway, it seems, and most talent<i> will</i> be =
affected=E2=80=94at best by a smaller-than-anticipated cost-of-living raise=
, often by a pay cut, and, at worst, by a delicately choreographed defenest=
ration. There <i>may</i> be a few exceptions to the rule=E2=80=94Savannah, =
the multitalented NBC headliner, who will become even <i>more </i>valuable =
to the brand in Hoda=E2=80=99s absence; <b>David Muir</b>, whose nightly br=
oadcast is often the most watched show on television, etcetera=E2=80=94but =
pretty much everyone else is vulnerable. =E2=80=9CIn this stage of the deco=
nstruction of linear television and network news, no one is safe,=E2=80=9D =
the media executive said.<br/><br/>In recent weeks, I=E2=80=99ve reported t=
hat <b>Lester Holt</b>, <b>Wolf Blitzer</b>, and other aging marquee talent=
s are likely to exit soon. I can also report that ABC News star <b>George S=
tephanopoulos </b>is currently in negotiations over his own $25 million-plu=
s contract, which is up early next year. All told, ABC
News pays him and his <i>Good Morning America</i> co-hosts, <b>Robin Robert=
s </b>and <b>Michael Strahan</b>, more than<i> $75 million </i>a year, an e=
xpense that represents nearly <i>half </i>of the roughly $200 million in an=
nual advertising revenue that <i>GMA </i>brings in. (By way of contrast, th=
e 75 employees that ABC News just laid off probably saved them around $15 m=
illion.) Stephanopoulos may soon determine he=E2=80=99s reached the top of =
the wave, too. (Strahan=E2=80=99s own negotiation is coming up later next y=
ear, and Robin=E2=80=99s the following.)<br/> <br/>Of course, the coming cu=
ts are not limited to megawatt, multimillion-dollar talent. In many cases, =
the most life-altering hits will be felt by those in the middle. At MSNBC, =
for instance, <b>Jonathan Lemire</b> recently signaled that he no longer wa=
nts to host <i>Way Too Early</i>, his current $750,000-a-year gig, but want=
s <i>more </i>than the customary $250,000-a-year contributor contract to co=
ntinue working as a <i>Morning
Joe </i>regular. <b>Joe Scarborough </b>himself told Lemire he would go to =
NBC News chief <b>Cesar Conde </b>and NBCUniversal C.E.O. <b>Mike Cavanagh<=
/b> and even Comcast C.E.O. <b>Brian Roberts </b>to argue on his behalf, bu=
